committed by YouTube users. The issue here

00:02:20.370 --> 00:02:24.150
was whether YouTube complied with Section
512 of The Copyright Act, which was added

00:02:24.150 --> 00:02:29.430
in 1998 as part of the Digital Millennium
Copyright Act, or DMCA. The DMCA sets out

00:02:29.430 --> 00:02:34.650
safe harbors to protect Internet Service Providers
or ISPs from unreasonable liability. Basically,

00:02:34.650 --> 00:02:40.020
certain ISPs have to block or remove infringing content that it's aware of, or for which it receives a valid notice.

00:02:40.020 --> 00:02:44.400
DMCA safe harbors protect Internet Service
Providers that comply with certain conditions

00:02:44.409 --> 00:02:47.819
when they're engaged in one of four covered
activities. The first activity is when they're

00:02:47.819 --> 00:02:52.519
acting as 'mere conduits', like the pipes
of the internet, for example, Comcast, Verizon

00:02:52.519 --> 00:02:56.599
Fios, or Google Fiber. The second activity
is caching content, like Google does. The

00:02:56.599 --> 00:03:00.959
third activity is hosting user-generated content,
like YouTube, and the fourth is acting as

00:03:00.959 --> 00:03:04.739
an information location tool or search engine,
like Google or Bing.

00:03:04.739 --> 00:03:08.780
The problem is, Congress came up with these
categories in 1998, which is like 80 years

00:03:08.780 --> 00:03:12.950
ago in internet years. The DMCA doesn't fit
neatly with new categories of online services

00:03:12.950 --> 00:03:18.060
including peer-to-peer sharing, torrents, and
cloud storage. The DMCA is due for an upgrade.

00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:22.040
Let's take a closer look at the notice and takedown provision of the DMCA in the Thought Bubble.

00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:26.180
So ISPs don't have to actively monitor for
infringement, but they do have to act if they

00:03:26.180 --> 00:03:30.379
know about infringing content. ISPs know there's
infringing content on their system when they

00:03:30.379 --> 00:03:34.579
receive a takedown notice or when they're
independently aware of it through either actual

00:03:34.579 --> 00:03:39.639
knowledge or where it's obvious infringing activity
is going on. This is called 'red flag knowledge.'

00:03:39.650 --> 00:03:44.190
Copyright owners and ISPs complain that the
notice and takedown system isn't working.

00:03:44.190 --> 00:03:48.099
Rights holders complain that the system only
works for large corporate entities. Individuals

00:03:48.099 --> 00:03:51.999
and small businesses can't afford to constantly
monitor for infringement and send thousands

00:03:51.999 --> 00:03:57.159
of notices. Also the DMCA requires that content
be taken down only from the specific location

00:03:57.159 --> 00:04:02.599
or URL identified in the notice. Once infringing
content, like Interstellar posted on YouTube,

00:04:02.599 --> 00:04:07.180
is taken down, it just gets reposted in a
different location. Copyright owners call

00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:12.400
it the whack-a-mole problem. ISPs complain
that the volume of takedown notices is overwhelming.

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:15.959
Google started keeping track of the take down
notices over the past several years. The number

00:04:15.959 --> 00:04:21.810
has increased from about a 130,000 URLs per
week in 2011 to nearly 10 million per week

00:04:21.810 --> 00:04:27.090
in 2015. Lots of these notices are sent using
automated systems, which sometimes leads to

00:04:27.090 --> 00:04:31.169
erroneously removed content that doesn't and
can't take into account the fact that the

00:04:31.169 --> 00:04:35.470
use might be fair. Also, there is some evidence
that the take down system is being abused

00:04:35.470 --> 00:04:39.180
as a censorship tool, as in the case where
some candidates' political advertisements

00:04:39.180 --> 00:04:42.690
have been targeted for removal during the
days leading up to a campaign, or as in the

00:04:42.690 --> 00:04:47.760
case of video game companies flagging unfavorable
reviews as infringing content. Thanks Thought Bubble.

